# 4. Undefined Data Type

The Undefined data type represents a variable that has been declared but not assigned any value. When a variable is created without
initialization, JavaScript automatically assigns it the value `undefined`. This data type helps programmers identify missing or 
incomplete data. Functions without return values also return undefined. Undefined is different from null because undefined means
“value not assigned,” while null means “empty value assigned intentionally.” Understanding undefined helps avoid runtime errors and 
improves debugging in applications.

### Example

```javascript id="d6k2mn"
let marks;

document.write(marks);
```

### Output

```javascript id="n5ub7m"
undefined
```

---

# 5. Null Data Type

The Null data type represents an intentional absence of value. Programmers use `null` when they want to clear or reset a
variable value. It is commonly used in databases, APIs, and object handling. Unlike undefined, null is assigned intentionally
by the developer. Null helps indicate that data is empty or unavailable. Although JavaScript shows null as an object internally,
it is considered a primitive data type. Proper use of null improves memory management and application reliability.

### Example

```javascript id="1m8wya"
let account = null;

document.write(account);
```

### Output

```javascript id="hxyo09"
null
```

---

# 6. BigInt Data Type

The BigInt data type is used to store very large integer values that cannot be handled safely by the normal Number type.
BigInt values are written by adding `n` at the end of a number. This data type is useful in scientific calculations,
cryptography, banking systems, and large databases where very large numbers are required. BigInt prevents precision loss during 
calculations involving huge integers. However, BigInt values cannot be mixed directly with regular numbers in operations.

### Example

```javascript id="l05vr5"
let bigNumber = 12345678901234567890n;

document.write(bigNumber);
```

### Output

```javascript id="9z23lj"
12345678901234567890
```

---

# 7. Symbol Data Type

The Symbol data type is used to create unique identifiers in JavaScript. Every symbol created is unique even if the 
descriptions are the same. Symbols are mainly used in objects to avoid duplicate property names. They improve security and 
reliability in object handling. Symbols are created using the `Symbol()` function. This data type is commonly used in advanced 
JavaScript programming and framework development. Symbols help developers create hidden or private object properties.

### Example

```javascript id="tzh4a8"
let id = Symbol("id");

document.write(id.toString());
```

### Output

```javascript id="08jn3y"
Symbol(id)
```

---

# 8. Object Data Type

The Object data type is a non-primitive data type used to store collections of data as key-value pairs. Objects can contain
properties and methods that represent real-world entities such as students, employees, products, and cars. JavaScript objects 
are flexible because properties can be added or removed dynamically. Arrays and functions are also considered objects in JavaScript.
Objects are widely used in APIs, databases, and web applications because they help organize and manage complex data efficiently.

### Example

```javascript id="qu0k8j"
let student = {
    name: "Ritika",
    age: 21
};

document.write(student.name);
document.write("<br>");
document.write(student.age);
```

### Output

```javascript id="ltq7ta"
Ritika
21
```
